–after 1129":"1093–after 1129","1083–1136":"1083–1136","1084–1120":"1084–1120","1090–1135":"1090–1135","1093–1129":"1093–1129","1095–1175":"1095–1175","1096–1129":"1096–1129","1110–1163":"1110–1163","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1048–1107":"1048–1107","1064–1136":"1064–1136","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1064":"1064","1163":"1163","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1084":"1084","1083":"1083","1093":"1093","1129":"1129","1107":"1107","1106":"1106","after 1129":"after 1129","1048":"1048","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","9 September 1107":"9 September 1107","Abt 1080":"about 1080","Framlingham Castle, Thetford, Norfolk, England":"Thetford, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bigod","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jaroslaw, Jozef, Krystyna, Slawomir.","Polish and Jewish (from Poland): from <i>bigos</i>, formerlydenoting anything that was chopped or slashed, now a particular dishcomposed of hash and sauerkraut; also ‘confusion’; hence perhaps anickname for someone who caused confusion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":3,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":13,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Bigod was born in 1093, in Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England, her father, Roger Bigod 1st Earl of Norfolk, was 45 and her mother, Adelise de Tosny, was 30. She had at least 1 son with Richard Fitz Euchace. She died after 1129."},"et":{"1093–after 1129":"1093–pärast 1129","1083–1136":"1083–1136","1084–1120":"1084–1120","1090–1135":"1090–1135","1093–1129":"1093–1129","1095–1175":"1095–1175","1096–1129":"1096–1129","1110–1163":"1110–1163","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1048–1107":"1048–1107","1064–1136":"1064–1136","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1064":"1064","1163":"1163","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1084":"1084","1083":"1083","1093":"1093","1129":"1129","1107":"1107","1106":"1106","after 1129":